abstract: >-
  A 3-minute classroom demonstration of embodied AI on a single MacBook,
  combining the NVIDIA Newton XPBD physics engine, a 2D pygame UI, and
  the Claude command-line client as the Vision-Language-Action (VLA) brain.
  The system offers three interaction modes: closed-form MPC ball catching,
  natural-language pick-and-stack via Claude (with a 1 ms keyword preflight
  that runs in parallel and removes the audience's perception of LLM
  latency), and decorative gestures. An optional industrial dual-arm mode
  adds a second fixed-base arm; a collaborative mode has the two arms relay
  blocks through a handoff slot to build and tear down a tower together,
  and a real-blocks mode simulates the blocks as genuine rigid bodies with
  a kinematic-toggle grasp, showing multi-agent coordination over a shared
  world. 228 unit and integration tests, 60.5 fps average on CPU-only
  Apple Silicon, no GPU and no cloud required.
